</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>SR118:v99#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="SR118"/><meta name="dc:title" content="SR &#xA;              118-&#xA;                INTRODUCED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Resolution
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 118</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Niello<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>June 11, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> Relative to Prostate Cancer Awareness Month. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SR 118, as introduced, Niello.
                          </span></div><div><span id="digesttext"/></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><span class="Resolution" title="source: /caml:MeasureDoc/caml:Resolution&#xA;    "><span class="Whereas" id="id_EB481D4E-A882-4FC3-A39D-3AE3601FC27B"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Prostate cancer is the most commonly diagnosed nonskin cancer and the second leading cause of cancer-related deaths among men in the United States; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_3CA26DBE-13C1-400E-9A0C-A1BD6E120EE5"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Approximately 333,830 men in the United States will be diagnosed with prostate cancer in 2026, and approximately 36,320 men will die from the disease, equating to one death every 15 minutes; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_6A226084-EEC2-4490-A143-DB30491649E6"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, More than 3,300,000 men in the United States are currently living with prostate cancer; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_AAD1E97B-2E45-4860-A00C-00C6AC18222D"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, One in 8 men will be diagnosed with prostate cancer during their lifetime, and 1 in 41 will die from the disease; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_9DA5F596-962B-4E4B-8BA2-60DC33C1C6D7"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, African American men face disproportionately higher risks, with approximately one in six diagnosed and mortality rates nearly twice that of other populations; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_61BCABA1-F2B8-413D-AF41-CDC47427B94E"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The risk of prostate cancer increases significantly after 50 years of age and is higher among individuals with a family history of the disease; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_688287F7-6646-4A57-9383-EEF63AB629C4"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Prostate cancer often presents no noticeable symptoms in its early stages, making early detection through appropriate screening critically important; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_6EFA2101-1902-4920-A102-FF241A73D3BB"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Screening methods, including prostate-specific antigen blood tests and digital rectal examinations, may detect prostate cancer at an early and more treatable stage; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_620AD7FC-D5EE-4635-B1A2-1C58B92E4C8A"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, When detected early, the survival rate for localized and regional prostate cancer approaches nearly 100 percent, while survival rates drop significantly once the cancer has metastasized; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_033EECE4-2EF4-4FA5-A547-BF8CC938F592"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Recent trends indicate that prostate cancer screening and routine testing may decline or be discontinued for some patients without adequate consultation or understanding of the associated risks; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_5FD65764-9589-4BD6-84DA-7C87B783D8DA"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, It is essential that patients are aware of any changes to recommended testing practices and are empowered to make informed decisions about their health; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_4C0F882A-A52C-4054-9F80-F0926FEEE0F2"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Individuals are strongly encouraged to speak with their physicians to understand their personal risk factors, the benefits and risks of screening, and whether continued testing is appropriate for them; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_9B9246AA-739A-4FE7-AB87-053058B14CAC"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Increasing public awareness, education, and proactive communication between patients and health care providers can save lives and protect families; now, therefore, be it</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_65F7F338-5C2A-42F6-BD30-E726CC320356"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved by the Senate of the State of California, That the Senate hereby designates September 2026 as Prostate Cancer Awareness Month in California; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_F62547E6-3D75-4888-87A5-B9D3967B7437"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Senate encourages all individuals, particularly those at higher risk, to engage in informed discussions with their health care providers regarding prostate cancer screening and early detection; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_CAF92526-A0BA-4DD6-8044-DBBB20264B28"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Senate urges increased awareness of the importance of continued vigilance in prostate cancer testing; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_0F5813E0-B33A-4CA9-B393-890379B2A1CF"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Secretary of the Senate transmit copies of this resolution to the author for appropriate distribution.</div></span></span></div></body></html>
